==Old English==
Common Germanic *''[[twai]]'' from Proto-Indo-European *''dwô''. Cognates include Old Saxon ''twā'', ''twō'' (Dutch ''[[twee]]''), Old High German ''[[zwēne]]'' (German ''[[zwei]]''), Old Norse ''[[tvær]]'' (Icelandic ''[[tveir]]'', Danish ''[[to]]'', Swedish ''[[två]]''), Latin ''[[duo]]'', Greek ''[[δύο]]'', Common Slavic *''[[dva]]'' (Russian ''[[два]]''). Combining form ''twi-'', cognate with German ''zwi-'', [[Sanskrit]] [[द्वि]] (''dwi-'').
